    "Confusions of this type put researchers' ability to falsify causal hypotheses about religious beliefs and cooperation at risk since, if a correlation was not discovered in a dataset, the former circular definition warrants the inference that the dataset represented a 'low' not a 'high' god (Nichols et al. (2020: 4), and see Table 1 in that paper for similar logical problems in this subfield; see Lightner et al. (2023), on the empirical implications of these conflations).",
